  "opinion": "As a retired woman who grew up in a small town in Pennsylvania and later moved to Philadelphia, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape people's experiences. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, lived experience for many. When students or professionals from underrepresented groups hear that they're 'not good at math' or 'don't belong in science,' it creates anxiety that can impair their performance. I remember when my own daughter was in high school and struggled with calculus; she felt the weight of expectations because she was the first in her family to go to college. That pressure, that fear of confirming a stereotype, is what stereotype threat is all about. It's not just about numbers or test scores—it's about the psychological burden that can hold someone back. We absolutely should address this. In my community, we've seen the power of mentorship and inclusive teaching methods. When teachers take the time to understand a student's background and build confidence, it makes a real difference. I've also found that creating safe spaces where students can discuss their challenges without judgment helps reduce the anxiety. As someone who has spent decades reading novels and playing board games, I know that storytelling and connection can break down barriers. The key is to recognize that everyone has the potential to succeed, and the system should be designed to nurture that potential. Addressing stereotype threat means changing the way we teach, the way we interact, and the way we believe in one another. It's not a matter of fixing people—it's about fixing the environment.",
